Value at Risk (VaR)¶

Historical & Parametric¶

The code is focusing on calculating the Value at Risk (VaR) with 2 approaches for a portfolio of assets.

Key Steps in the Code:

  1. System initialization: It fetches historical data of specified assets using yfinance.
  2. Data overview: Plots the adjusted closing prices of these assets to visualize their performance over time.
  3. Portfolio Returns Calculation: Computes logarithmic returns of the assets and then calculates the portfolio returns based on equal weighting of each asset.
  4. VaR Calculation

Historical VaR vs. Parametric VaR

  • Historical VaR: This method involves ranking the historical returns and picking the VaR as a percentile of these returns. It is non-parametric and does not assume a normal distribution of returns.

  • Parametric VaR (also known as Variance-Covariance VaR): This method relies on assumptions about the distribution of returns (usually a normal distribution). It uses the mean and standard deviation of the returns to estimate VaR.

Github: jfbl369 | www.jfbl.me | Jean-Franois Berger-Lefbure

VaR Calculation¶

VaR historical¶

In [139]:
confidence_interval_h = 0.99
VaR_h = np.percentile(range_returns, 100 - (confidence_interval_h * 100))*portfolio_value

return_window = 25
range_returns = historical_returns.rolling(window=return_window).sum()
range_returns = range_returns.dropna()
range_returns_dollar = range_returns * portfolio_value

plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))

VaR parametric¶

In [123]:
days = 25
historical_x_day_returns = historical_returns.rolling(window=days).sum()
cov_matrix = log_returns.cov() * 252
portfolio_std_dev = np.sqrt(weights.T @ cov_matrix @ weights)
historical_x_day_returns_dollar = historical_x_day_returns * portfolio_value
In [80]:
confidence_interval_p = 0.99
VaR_p = portfolio_value * (norm.ppf(1 - confidence_interval_p) * portfolio_std_dev * np.sqrt(days / 252) - historical_returns.mean() * days)
In [121]:
